  "original_lang": "ta",
  "original_title": "\u0baa\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0b95\u0baa\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bc8 \u0b87\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bbe \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bb3\u0bcd",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "A day without a book bag",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "Madhya Pradesh has decided to observe one day a week as a book bag free day to reduce the burden of school children's book bags. Guidelines for this have been published.",
        "According to the government, the Madhya Pradesh government has adopted this scheme based on the National Education Policy. This is said to be applicable to all government and private schools in the state.",
        "Accordingly, the book bag of 1st and 2nd class students should be between 1.6 to 2.2 kg in weight. The mass of a book bag for class 3 to 5 students may be 1.7 to 2.5 kg. A book bag for class 6 and 7 students may weigh between 2 kg and 3 kg. A book bag for an eighth grader can be between 2.5 kg and 4.5 kg. Bag of 9th and 10th students may be 2.5 kg to 4.5 kg.",
        "In this case, the weight of the book bag of class 11 and 12 students in high school will be determined by the respective school management according to the subject chosen by the students.",
        "Apart from this, the students up to class 8 can keep practice books and handwriting practice books in the classroom. The circular also said that students up to class 8 are not required to bring textbooks related to computer science, morals, general science, health, physical education, sports and arts to schools."
      ],
